txt_feedback_2:
Feedback:
On the household data section it asked which is my primary car. I put the lower range EV of the two cars because it is *my* primary car, although the longer range EV is used more (by my wife). I’m not sure how you intended that so if you are trying to get the primary car used by the household you may want to clarify. 
On the baseline question I answered that I manage charging on “an app” because it was the closest fit. What I meant is it’s a feature on my VW’s on-board controls to do scheduled charging (e.g. 40% minimum, then fill to max 90% by 8am). Equivalent to an OEM app but I don’t use a mobile UI for it. 
On the V2G section it’s unclear whether the guarantees will happen within 8 hours of beginning the session or 8 hours after the event. For example if I’m charging overnight for 12 hours  from 8pm to 8am, can V2G drain me down to the minimum at 7am and then leave me short of the guarantee when I’m leaving for work at 8am? 
Also one of the program description pages has a typo at the bottom of it on the word “charging”.
Good luck! Exciting to see research advancing in this area.

txt_feedback_2: Because I am a very high mileage daily driver averaging 50-150 a day, I am less interested in receiving money back from the utility for V2G bi directional charging. My interest in it is for home backup. I already own the 75kwh battery in my car. The equivalent cost of  80kwh  solar battery storage (Enphase 5P units plus associated gear) is  $105,000 in my market and my home’s electric panel can only handle 40 kwh anyway. I sell solar + batteries professionally. Tesla also won’t turn on V2G anytime soon. Without the software instructions in the car’s onboard charging port for two way flow, a third party bidirectional charger simply won’t work. They won’t enable it because  the capability competes directly with their Powerwall  3 product. Because Tesla has the largest market share of BEVs in the US, this is going to be a large stumbling block for the utilities to roll out effective V2G programs. Uptake will be limited to non-Teslas owners, which is a much smaller pool.
